\subsection*{Preface}
We now construct a complete geometric derivation of temporal tilt in the O-cross-I framework. Our goal is to show how the traditional Lorentz transformation arises from a simple rotation in a lifted coordinate space $(\tau, t_x, x)$ — where $\tau$ is universal time, $t_x$ is the local observer's time along a spatial direction $x$, and $x$ is ordinary space. This derivation proceeds in three steps:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Lift}: Lift the $(t, x)$ coordinate of the unprimed frame to $(\tau, t_x, x)$ using an angle $\alpha_x$.
  \item \textbf{Lift}: Lift the $(t', x')$ coordinate of the primed frame to $(\tau', t_x', x')$ using angle $-\alpha_x$.
  \item \textbf{Rotate}: Relate the lifted frames using a rotation in $(\tau, t_x)$ space.
